metadata.name: Dancing Line 燕舞 #187
metadata.description:
This work is inspired by thinking about lines. Points, lines, and surfaces are the most basic elements of art. Whether or not an art work can be made using only lines and colors is a direction that has been explored recently. By connecting points at different distances, the color and transparency can produce different light and shade effects with the change of distance. In addition, a rotation algorithm is generated during the connection process, which can create light and shade, density, and the beauty of curves with relatively rich layers. , like a swallow dancing in the air is the resulting arc path. Hence the name Yanwu. Of course, another Chinese meaning of Yanwu is a brand of early Chinese TV sets, which also commemorates the era of creativity. I am also grateful to be able to contribute to the construction of Web3. There are 3 background colors, 7 line colors, and 30 dance times in this work, among which there are millions of combinations of point positions. This work only displays the background color, line color and dance times in the feature information.
Made With P5.js.
20% of royalties will be donated to the Processing Foundation.

The following is the description in Chinese.
作品燕舞：
当足够的线条沿着特殊的轨迹进行排列，
并且线条的数量足够多的时候，
就会让画面给人以美感的同时，
产生足够震撼的力量。
燕舞因为生成过程有曲线路径，
像燕子在空中飞舞留下的痕迹。
当然燕舞的另外一个中文意思一个早期中国电视机的一个品牌，
也以此纪念那个创意勃发的年代。也同时希望能够为Web3贡献一份力量。
此作品共有3中背景色彩，7中线条色彩，以及30种舞动次数随机组合，
其中点的位置有百万种组合，此作品只把背景色，
线条颜色和舞动次数作品特色点显示在作品信息中，
此作品基于p5js语言完成

metadata.name: FXHASH Generative Logo #378
metadata.description:
Unique iteration of the first Generative Token minted on fxhash.

It also servers as the actual logo of the platform. It represents the generative processes driving fxhash tokens. Generative Tokens are fed with a unique hash to produce unique outputs based on the hash — they are functions with a hash as single input.

The growth that comes out of the text is driven by a "Dividing-Aggregating Walkers" (DAW) algorithm. The hash drives all the DAW settings, as well as a mutation factor which is responsible for changes in each Walker parameters as they divide.

Some iterations will produce very simple outputs whereas others might be more chaotic.

Piece by @ciphrd for fxhash

metadata.name: Pastoral Palettes #192
metadata.description:
Pastoral Palettes showcases 93 beautiful hand tuned palettes in a generative pastoral setting. The palettes themselves pay homage to great paintings from the past up to the present. Isolating the palettes in this way brings out the artistic genius of the underlying artwork in a unique way. The palette name in the features contains the painting and artist.

The algorithmic parts of Pastoral Palettes use many techniques to create the scene and generate the ground, sky, trees, and shrubbery. Using random perlin noise for the placement ensures a more natural looking scene. The sky is a gradient composed from the palette. Each blade of grass is drawn individually using perlin noise to create the color pattern in the grass. Each tree and shrub is randomly constructed and colored using color blending in the transition colors. The grass generation is the most computationally expensive and the density can be adjusted with the arrow keys, see below.

The mint size is relatively small in relation to the number of palettes, so to ensure that all palettes get generated at least once, we are including 2 palettes for each mint.

Each mint of Pastoral Palettes comes with sunlight and moonlight views, toggled with the 'f' key. The palettes look strikingly different for each view - you can choose which one you like best.

Variations:

 - Each palette has an equal chance of being minted. Since the mint size is so small compared to the number of palettes, there is a high chance of getting a rare palette. 
 - 2% chance of getting 5 palettes instead of the default of 2. 
 - 10% chance of getting a sun/moon in the sky.
 - Each layout will be entirely unique.

Pastoral Palettes is responsive and looks great on any size display. They look especially good on large displays of 2K, 4K, and even 8K.

'f' flips between sunlight and moonlight views.
'p' cycles through the palettes.
's' saves an image in the exact size of the current display.
'up/down arrow' adjusts the grass density. Denser grass may look better at some resolutions, but takes considerably longer to render, particularly on large displays.
